{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475994"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13116"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13116"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.04,0.74,0.01,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5553"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5553"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"148"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46083"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, irritability, and reduced oral intake. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 39.2\u00b0C, pulse rate 156/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, and SpO2 99% on room air. He has bilateral non-exudative conjunctivitis, cracked red lips, a strawberry tongue, and cervical lymphadenopathy. There is a polymorphous rash on his trunk and extremities. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous immunoglobulin and ibuprofen","Low-dose aspirin alone","Intravenous immunoglobulin and low-dose aspirin","Start a TNF inhibitor","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child\u0027s presentation is consistent with Kawasaki disease, which is diagnosed based on fever \u22655 days and at least four out of five principal clinical features: bilateral bulbar conjunctival injection, oral mucous membrane changes, peripheral extremity changes, polymorphous rash, and cervical lymphadenopathy. The mainstay of treatment is intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) and aspirin, which should be initiated as soon as the diagnosis is made to reduce the risk of serious cardiac complications such as coronary artery aneurysms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn 2017 review of six studies found (in tandem with IVIG use) no difference in the prevalence of coronary artery aneurysms in patients treated with low-dose compared with high-dose aspirin. For this reason, current guidelines recommend the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) and low-dose aspirin.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous immunoglobulin and ibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is close to the correct treatment, but aspirin is preferred over ibuprofen in Kawasaki disease due to its anti-inflammatory and anti-platelet effects. Other non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) should be also avoided whilst using aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-dose aspirin alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for initial treatment. Part of the management of Kawasaki disease is low-dose aspirin (3-5 mg/kg/day), which appears to be non-inferior to high-dose aspirin in preventing coronary artery complications; the other component of treatment is intravenous immunoglobulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETNF inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E such as infliximab have been studied in Kawasaki disease, particularly in IVIG-resistant cases. However, they are not considered first-line therapy and should only be considered in refractory cases under specialist guidance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used as adjunctive therapy in high-risk patients or those who fail to respond to initial IVIG treatment. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital guidelines state their use may be beneficial in particular high-risk groups (including age \u003C12 months, cardiac/coronary artery involvement on echocardiogram at presentation, or CRP \u003E100 mg/L). However, it is not part of the standard initial treatment regimen for Kawasaki disease, and the optimal dose and duration of steroids in treatment of Kawasaki disease is poorly described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of IVIG and aspirin has been shown to be most effective in reducing inflammation, preventing coronary artery abnormalities, and improving outcomes in Kawasaki disease. Prompt initiation of this treatment is crucial to prevent potentially life-threatening cardiac sequelae. Untreated Kawasaki disease carries a 25% risk of developing coronary artery aneurysms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intravenous immunoglobulin and low-dose aspirin are the mainstay of treatment for Kawasaki disease.","Untreated Kawasaki disease can lead to serious cardiac complications such as coronary artery aneurysms.","The correct dosage and combination of treatments are crucial in managing Kawasaki disease effectively."],"references":["Sundel R. Kawasaki disease: Clinical features and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/kawasaki-disease-clinical-features-and-diagnosis","Golshevsky D, Cheung M, Burgner D. Kawasaki disease- the importance of prompt recognition and early referral. Aust Fam Physician. 2013;42(7):473-6. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/9125ecdc-7fd9-4339-8ebc-ce3ad73cfd72/Kawasaki-disease.aspx","Kawasaki disease. Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne. Updated January 2021. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Kawasaki_disease/","Ho LGY, Curtis N. What dose of aspirin should be used in the initial treatment of Kawasaki disease? Arch Dis Child. 2017 Dec;102(12):1180-1182. doi: 10.1136/archdischild-2017-313538. Epub 2017 Oct 24. PMID: 29066520."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13116"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T16:09:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-31T13:16:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5553"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type